{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500475"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:15:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1653"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.77,0.06,0.05,0.03,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101621"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"1212"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101621"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12 month history of numbness and weakness in his left hand. He has had difficulty holding objects in his hand and doing up the buttons on his shirt. He also reports numbness and tingling along his first and second fingers, which is worse at night. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include metformin and gliclazide. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of his left hand reveals wasting of the thenar eminence (Image). There is no loss of sensation over the thenar eminence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carpal tunnel syndrome","Cervical radiculopathy","Pronator teres syndrome","Thoracic outlet syndrome","Diabetic neuropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is wasting of the thenar muscles. Whilst any of the mentioned conditions could produce these changes, the most likely and commonest explanation would be the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. The median nerve has been compressed under the flexor retinaculum, leading to denervation and subsequent atrophy of the thenar musculature. Diabetes is a known risk factor for developing carpal tunnel syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical (C6) radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E could be a differential diagnosis, given the dermatome that is affected. However, there is no mention of reduced reflexes (such as the brachialis and biceps reflex). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPronator teres syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the compression of the median nerve between the humeral and ulnar heads of the pronator teres and would present with thenar atrophy. However, this proximal lesion would result in impaired sensation over the thenar eminence, because it would affect the palmar cutaneous branch of the median nerve as well. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile\u003Cstrong\u003E thoracic outlet syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a good consideration, the patient does not present with signs of subclavian artery/vein compression (limb ischaemia or venous distension). Brachial plexus compression is also unlikely, given the lack of neck pain and only the thenar eminence muscle group being affected in isolation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic hyperglycaemia in diabetes mellitus could cause progressive damage to peripheral and autonomic nerves. The resulting peripheral \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a symmetrical loss of sensation of the peripheries, including the legs. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paresthesia of the lateral fingers and thenar eminence atrophy in a patient with diabetes is highly suggestive of carpal tunnel syndrome.","Carpal tunnel syndrome typically presents with numbness and tingling in the thumb, index, middle, and lateral half of the ring finger, with symptoms often worsening at night.","The palmar cutaneous branch of the median nerve branches proximal to the carpal tunnel, which is why sensation over the thenar eminence is preserved in carpal tunnel syndrome."],"references":["Padua L, Coraci D, Erra C, Pazzaglia C, Paolasso I, Loreti C, et al. Carpal tunnel syndrome: clinical features, diagnosis, and management. The Lancet Neurology. 2016 Nov;15(12):1273\u201384. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27751557/","Sevy JO, Sina RE, Varacallo MA. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Oct 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448179/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18462"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18462"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/901b8af7-b10f-4f40-8322-f8b7cd0ff752.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://a